"Slovenian: topographic name derived from <i>rob</i> ‘edge, border’ (see   Robar  )."]}]},{"name":"Frank","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin. The name referred originally to a member of the tribe of the Franks, who are said to have got the name from a characteristic type of spear that they used. When the Franks migrated into Gaul in the 4th century, the country received its modern name of France (Late Latin <i>Francia</i>) and the tribal term Frank came to mean ‘Frenchman’. The name is now also used as a short form of   Francis   or   Franklin ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"O.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Oh","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":34,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":43,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":54,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":56,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Frank O. Robbins was born in 1515, in Kent, England, his father, Edmund Robyns I, was 21 and his mother, Abigail Worton, was 16. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Elizabeth Joan Palmer. He died in 1575, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1515–1575":"1515–1575","1532–1627":"1532–1627","–Female":"Surnud","1520–1559":"1520–1559","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1495–1532":"1495–1532","1499–1550":"1499–1550","1550":"1550","1495":"1495","1571":"1571","Abt 1532":"umbes 1532","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1499":"1499","1532":"1532","1520":"1520","1575":"1575","1530":"1530","1627":"1627","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1559":"1559","England":"England","Stourton, Warwickshire, England":"Stourton, Warwickshire, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Harrowden, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrowden, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United King